        "excerpt": "So they moved out for the first time according to the commandment of the LORD through Moses.",
        "body": "The departure on the twentieth day of the second month (10:11) is the Pentateuch's most precisely dated movement since the giving of the law at Sinai (Exodus 19:1). The precision is itself theological — the narrator wants the reader to know that God's timing is exact, that the eleven-month formation period was not vague spiritual incubation but purposeful preparation culminating in a specific day. When the cloud lifted, it lifted on schedule — God's schedule.\n\nThe march order described in 10:14-28 is the theological arrangement of Numbers 2 made kinetic. Judah leads — the tribe of the scepter (Genesis 49:10), the tribe from which the Davidic line and ultimately the Messiah will come. The Levitical order is theologically careful: Gershon and Merari, who carry the tabernacle's structural components, set out after the first tribal grouping (10:17) so that by the time the Kohathites arrive with the holy objects (10:21), the tent is already erected. The LORD's dwelling place is never without a home at any stopping point. God's logistics of worship anticipate the need before the need arrives.\n\nDan forms the rear guard (10:25), and the Hebrew asaph (gatherer, collector) suggests the rear guard's function was not merely military protection but the gathering of those who fell behind. The march cares for its stragglers. The named leaders across 10:14-27 — Nahshon, Nethanel, Eliab, Elizur, Shelumiel, Eliasaph, Elishama, Gamaliel, Abidan, Ahiezer, Pagiel, Ahira — are the same men who brought the dedicatory offerings at the tabernacle's consecration in Numbers 7. They are not functionaries; they are the named, accountable leaders of a named, accountable people. The list is a roll call of covenant responsibility.\n\nThe narrator's closing summary (10:28) — 'this was the order of march of the sons of Israel by their armies as they set out' — frames the entire procession as a military campaign (*tsava*, armies). Israel is not wandering; it is advancing under orders. The journey is covenanted purposeful movement from the mountain of revelation to the land of promise. Everything in between is the test of whether the formation will hold.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nasa* (set out, journey) — the chapter's dominant verb, appearing more than seventeen times. Its literal sense is 'to pull up,' as tent pegs are pulled up when a camp breaks. The repetition creates a liturgy of departure: tribe after tribe, clan after clan, all pulling up their pegs under the same command. *Degel* (standard, banner) appears in Numbers 2 as the organizing center of each tribal camp; in chapter 10 the same degel marks the moving column. The march replicates the camp — the theology of arrangement does not change when the community is on the move."
