        "body": "The Hobab episode is the chapter's most theologically provocative section because it raises a question the text does not fully answer: when God's guidance is available through cloud and ark, is it appropriate — even faithful — to also seek experienced human wisdom? Moses' appeal to his father-in-law is urgent and personal. He moves from covenant promise ('the LORD has promised good concerning Israel,' 10:29) to pragmatic need ('you know where we should camp in the wilderness, and you will be as eyes for us,' 10:31) when the first appeal fails. The word 'eyes' (*ayin*, 10:31) is striking — Moses is asking Hobab to serve a function that the pillar of cloud already serves in 9:17-22.\n\nThe text records Hobab's refusal but does not record his final decision. Judges 1:16 notes that the descendants of Moses' father-in-law went up with Judah from the city of palms to the wilderness of Judah — suggesting Hobab eventually came, or at minimum that his family joined Israel's journey. The Old Testament is comfortable with this ambiguity because the theological point does not rest on Hobab's decision. It rests on what the narrator does next: immediately after the Hobab dialogue, the ark goes before Israel 'to seek out a resting place for them' (10:33). The true navigator is positioned in front — the human expert, if he came, followed behind.\n\nCalvin, in his commentary on Numbers, sees in this episode the doctrine of secondary causes: God ordains means as part of His providential governance, and using those means is not unbelief but wisdom. The Israelite is not to despise Hobab's wilderness knowledge any more than he is to despise the physician's medicine. The error would be to trust human eyes as the primary guide while the ark and cloud are available. Peter Davids' broader principle on this kind of wisdom literature is apt: God's sovereignty and human responsibility operate in ordered relation, not competition. The Hobab episode models that relation — earnest use of human wisdom, primary reliance on divine presence.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yatav* (to do good, treat well) appears twice in Moses' appeal — 'we will do you good' (v.29) and 'we will share with you' (v.32). The verb picks up the *tov* (good) of the Abrahamic promise: the good God promised Abraham flows outward to those who attach themselves to his descendants. Moses is offering Hobab a share in the Abrahamic inheritance. *Ayin* (eyes) — used here metaphorically for local knowledge and discernment of terrain; the same word the spies use of themselves in Numbers 13:33 ('we were like grasshoppers in our own eyes')."
